Zo vaak trip ik niet (7 keer waarvan 2 op een bepaald moment "bad" gingen).
Minder snel bad gaan kan alleen met goede voorbereiding, zorgen dat de set en setting goed zijn. Daar hoort ook je mindset bij. Wat voor mij helpt tijdens een trip is fruit eten en dan vooral zoet fruit dat redelijk sappig is zoals een mango of aardbeien. Water drinken kan helpen, maar persoonlijk heb ik liever thee. Temperatuur kan ook een rol spelen, zorg dat je het koud hebt, maar ook weer niet te warm.
En zorg voor muziek waar je je fijn bij voelt en die geen negatieve gevoelens opwekken. Voor mij helpt op dat soort momenten vooral psychedelische rock of pop zoals de Beach Boys of the Doors.
Laatste keer deed ik lsd op oud en nieuw en iemand zette iets van hardstyle of terrorcore op en dad gaf mij bad vibes waardoor ik mijzelf als de duivel zag, dat is niet hoe ik mij voel of wil zijn maar wel hoe ik het zag en dat is niet fijn.

Cap. XX - Il Bodhisattva Mai sprezzante

Mi ricordo di un tempo passato in cui c’era un Buddha chiamato Re Suono maestoso, dotato di poteri e saggezza sconfinati, guida e maestro di tutti, attorno a cui dei, uomini, draghi e spiriti si riunivano per tributargli offerte. Dopo la sua estinzione, quando anche la sua legge era sul punto di estinguersi, viveva un Bodhisattva che si chiamava Mai Sprezzante, in un epoca in cui c’erano monaci estremamente arroganti. Questo monaco, chiunque incontrasse, si inchinava e offriva parole di lode dicendo:

“Nutro per voi un profondo rispetto perché voi tutti state seguendo la via del Bodhisattva e certamente conseguirete la buddhità”

Questo monaco non si dedicava a leggere o proclamare le scritture ma se ne andava semplicemente in giro inchinandosi alla gente.
Tra le quattro categorie di credenti, però, c’erano molte persone che parlavano male di lui e lo insultavano. Trascorsero così molti anni durante i quali questo monaco fu disprezzato e ingiuriato. Tuttavia egli non si lasciava mai prendere dalla collera e anche quando lo picchiavano ripeteva
“Nutro per voi un profondo rispetto perché voi tutti state seguendo la via del Bodhisattva e certamente conseguirete la buddhità”
Per questo motivo egli fu soprannominato Mai sprezzante.
Quando questo monaco fu sul punto di morire, udì dall’alto dei cieli un milione di versi del Sutra del Loto che in precedenza era stato predicato dal Buddha Re Suono Maestoso. In quel momento allora acquistò la purezza della vista, dell’olfatto, dell’udito del corpo e della mente e la sua vita si allungò di duecentodiecimila milioni di nayuta di anni ed egli andò in giro in lungo e in largo predicando il Sutra del Loto.

Allora, le quattro categorie di credenti che fino a quel momento lo avevano disprezzato, vedendo che egli aveva acquistato tutte queste virtù sovrannaturali, udendo la sua predicazione presero fede in lui e volontariamente si fecero suoi fedeli seguaci.

Barisan Sosialis (English/Chinese:社会主义阵线/Socialist Front) was a political party in Singapore. The prominent founding members of the Barisan were Lee Siew Choh and Lim Chin Siong. It became the biggest opposition party in Singapore in the 1960s and the 1980s until Operation Coldstore and Spectrum.

The main objectives of the Barisan included eradicating colonialism, establishing a united independent and "democratic" Malayan nation comprising the Federation of Malaya and Singapore and introducing an hideous economic system to promote prosperity and stability in society. The remainder of the party was absorbed into the Worker's Party in 1988.

Lim Chin Siong was penpals with the likes of Pol Pot and Kim-Il-Sung and was so extreme in his rhetoric as seen in the picrel that the Worker's Party was originally a split off faction from Barisan. Over 120 members of the party were jailed for communist conspiracy, stripped of their citizenship, and deported to other nations never to return. Here are their experiences

Even funner fact: Spain didn't really "rule" the Philippines in the first 200 years of their colonial regime here. Nueva Espana administered Manila while Manila in turn... hoped that enough natives obeyed that day to carry out colonial policy.

You see there were too few Spaniards & Latins living in the Philippines that for most Native Filipinos, Spanish rule was nominal and they only agreed to it since its basically one big tribal confederation where tribes under Spain worked together to survive in the harsh world of 1500s-1700s SEAsia. Nevertheless whenever Spain does something the natives do not like, they resisted either via revolting or- more common enough- simply disobeying the Spic and/or running away into the wilderness. There were too few Spaniards anyway to chase after them.

To be fair, all Spain cared for during this time was their main trading port in Manila. So long as Manila was protected, the Natives paid their annual tribute, & showed up for whatever wars or projects Manila had in mind, Spain was ok with the autonomy of the Philippine natives.

All this changed in the 19th Century though when Spain lost its Latin American Colonies (especially Mexico) which forced the Spic to directly administrate the Philippines even more. This in turn pissed off Philippine elites who had enjoyed Spain's absentee colonialism, which eventually resulted to Filipino nationalism & independentism.

Okay. So, assuming:

- it's a typical woodchuck (around 3 kg)
- it's smart enough to chuck wood with the wind in his back
- the wood is wet but Lebanon cedar is not particularly known for absorbing much water. Density of dry Lebanon cedar is 520 kg/m3, let's say 600 to account for the water.
- woodchucks of that size dig burrows about 8 meters long and obviously have to throw the dirt out. I'm taking 1250 kg/m3 density for the dirt to get the volume a woodchuck can chuck in one day.

This gives us the somewhat incredible answer of "close to 300 kg a day". That is the amount of wood a woodchuck could chuck, if it decided to chuck wood.
And obviously, since European marmots (picrel), their cousins, are typically larger (around 5kg), they could possibly chuck half a ton a day.

>You said it was for receiving, not for the recipient
I said it was used for reception, to make it clear that the receiving party (the recipient) is in the dative case, since you didn't seem to be sure when mistakenly calling it genitive.

I'm not sure why you're so hung up things I never said or implied, but what gets me is that you argue about all of this from the perspective of German idiom, and completely fail to understand how syntax works. However you choose to express something in German has no impact on how syntactic correlation between subjects and objects works. If we look at the following clause syntactically:
>he gave me a book
We have subject - verb - indirect object - direct object.
If we look at classic IE cases, the normal thing to do nom v dat acc, mapping dative to the recipient of the action (indirect object of the verb), and accusative to the object affected by the action (the direct object of the verb). This is why you say "gib mir" and not "gib mich".

>As if that was it's defining feature.
Well, that is its true use case (pun intended), as even suggested by its very name. However, dative in Germanic languages has more to it; it's several cases (dative, locative, ablative, instrumental) that have historically merged, so that's why you have a wide range of uses for the dative.

All I did was point out why dative must be used, but you started going on about whether you'd say "he gave me a book" or "I got a book from him", completely missing the mark. It's honestly perplexing.

Apparently it takes 750 hours on average to get fluent in German, so if you can do 2 hours of effective study per day, you'd get there in 365 days.

In my opinion, courses are a time waste unless you use the hour to clear up any questions you have or just practice speaking to someone.
